{
  "texts": [
    "The more general cases arise as dual categories under gauging algebra objects A(H, ψ) in Vec ω G, which are simply characterized by non-anomalous subgroups H ⊂ G, with a choice of the discrete torsion in H 2 (H, U(1)) (ψ is a torsor under this group).",
    "This coincides with the defining data of C(G, ω, H, ψ) up to auto-equivalence.",
    "The corresponding module category is denoted as M(H, ψ), which is determined by (H, ψ) up to conjugations in (G, ω) [68,97] and is the invertible bimodule category for the Morita equivalence between the two fusion categories.",
    "For example, Rep(G) = C(G, 1, G, 1) is dual to Vec G by the module category M(G, 1), which has rank 1 (unique simple object), equivalently from the category of (A(G, 1), A(G, 1))-bimodules and A(G, 1) = ⊕ g∈G g is the regular representation of G. Such a rank 1 module category M(G, 1) ∼ = Vec realizes a fiber functor F: C → Vec = Fun(Vec, Vec) (here for C = Rep(G)) [11].",
    "Physically, the module category M(G, 1) ∼ = Vec corresponds to the topological interface from imposing Dirichlet boundary conditions for the G-gauge fields in the half-gauging picture (see section 2.3)."
  ]
}